[{"id":"VR619265","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A student has a calibrated spring scale that measures force with a precision of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"plus or minus 0.05 newton\"><math alttext=\"plus or minus 0.05 newton\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mo>±</mo><mn>0</mn><mstyle displaystyle=\"false\"><mtext>.</mtext></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"false\"><mn>05</mn></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"false\"><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"false\"><mtext>N</mtext></mstyle></mstyle></math></span></span>. At sea level, the student holds the scale vertically with a <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"100 gram\"><math alttext=\"100 gram\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>100</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></span></span> object attached to it, and the scale reads <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.00 newton\"><math alttext=\"1.00 newton\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn><mtext>.</mtext><mn>00</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>N</mtext></math></span></span>. The student then brings the scale and the object to the top of a <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1000 meter\"><math alttext=\"1000 meter\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1000</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>m</mtext></math></span></span> high mountain and again holds the scale vertically with the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"100 gram\"><math alttext=\"100 gram\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>100</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>g</mtext></math></span></span> object attached. Which of the following correctly describes the scale’s reading, and provides valid justification for the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR619265_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The scale reading is between <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.90 newton\"><math alttext=\"0.90 newton\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0</mn><mtext>.</mtext><mn>90</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>N</mtext></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.99 newton\"><math alttext=\"0.99 newton\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0</mn><mtext>.</mtext><mn>99</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>N</mtext></math></span></span>, because the scale is not precise enough to read the exact value of the object’s weight.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The scale reading is between <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.90 newton\"><math alttext=\"0.90 newton\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0.90</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.99 newton\"><math alttext=\"0.99 newton\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0.99</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></span></span>, because the weight of the object is inversely proportional to the square of the distance to the center of Earth.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The scale reading is between <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.95 newton\"><math alttext=\"0.95 newton\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0.95</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.05 newtons\"><math alttext=\"1.05 newtons\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1.05</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></span></span>, because the height of the mountain is negligible compared to the radius of the earth.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The scale reading is between <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.95 newton\"><math alttext=\"0.95 newton\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0.95</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.05 newtons\"><math alttext=\"1.05 newtons\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1.05</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></span></span>, because weight is an intrinsic property of an object which doesn’t change even when the gravitational field changes.</p>"],"answer":2}]